1 NAME Robert/Levis/
1 SEX M
1 BIRT
2 DATE 1558
2 PLAC England
1 NOTE Person Source
2 SOUR @S99@
1 NOTE Quote of unknown origin  A Robert Levis died in 1558 in Beeston
2 CONT near Nottingham and
2 CONT is buried there. This is the first mention of the Levis  family
2 CONT in England
2 CONT as French Huguenots seeking refuge. A  plausible time for
2 CONT migration would be after
2 CONT 1547. The family  became numerous in England between 1575 and
2 CONT 1684 and were of
2 CONT 'substance and high standing'. Information about the direct
2 CONT line to those that left
2 CONT for America is sparse, but  traceable.    [genealogy stuff
2 CONT included in db]
2 CONT 
2 CONT Meanwhile, back in France, by 1643, the Huguenots had  ceased
2 CONT to be a political
2 CONT entity in France, and their civil rights were confirmed in that
2 CONT year by the Edict
2 CONT of Nantes in  exchange for loyalty to the crown; however, the
2 CONT terms were not
2 CONT honored, and judicial persecution continued. In 1681, the
2 CONT Huguenots in Nimes and
2 CONT Montauban, were forced to abjure their religion en masse,
2 CONT allowing Louis XIV to
2 CONT declare that, since the best had embraced Catholicism, the
2 CONT Edict of Nantes was no
2 CONT longer necessary.
2 CONT 
2 CONT 1682 was to be a decisive year. In England, active
2 CONT persecutions of Friends continued,
2 CONT mostly taking a judicial form, but prompting many to leave for
2 CONT abroad. Within two
2 CONT years the harassment had diminished, and perhaps ceased
2 CONT entirely in the vicinity of
2 CONT London. However, the  persecutions were not definitively over
2 CONT until the Toleration
2 CONT Act of 1689.
2 CONT 
2 CONT In 1682 the ranking member of the de Levis family (probably a
2 CONT cousin) 'returned to
2 CONT France to reclaim his estates',  of necessity also returning to
2 CONT the Catholic church.
2 CONT (He  probably reasoned that a Dukedom was worth a mass...)
1 FAMS @F431@
1 REFN 723
1 CHAN
2 DATE 04 JUN 2016
