1 NAME William Wade/Hinshaw/
1 SEX M
1 NOTE Information from Nicole (Teasdale) Wing.  She says that his daughter, Anna Maria (Hinshaw) Wing, has/had a copy of a letter originally written by him to one of his sisters, excerpted below.
1 NOTE Genealogist and author of 'The Encyclopedia of American Quaker
2 CONT Genealogy'.
1 NOTE The following is an extract of a letter written to one of his sisters on 7 Dec 1929
2 NOTE 'The name should properly be pronounced Wickers-ham, meaning Wickers home, or the home of the Wicker makers.  It was originally  Wickersheim,and the family was founded in Alsace, France; then they  we
3 CONC nt to England.  Thomas Wickersham was born in Bolney, Sussex Co.,  England (60 miles from London) about the year 1660.  He died in  Chester Co. Pa., in 1730.  He had two wives, the 1st was Ann Grover,
3 CONC of Hurstperpoint, Sussex, Eng.; she died there when her 4th child was 3 1/2 years old, in 1697.  He married again in 1700 one Alice  Hogge, who came to America with him in 1700 and who bore him 7 chil
3 CONC dren, of which James (our ancestor) was one. Thomas Wickersham was an ardent Quaker, and was made an Elder, and then a Minister. He helped to build the old Kennett Meeting House, in Marlborough Twp.
3 CONC ,  Chester Co., Pa., which was located near his house.  He was a farmer,  and had 1000 acres in Pa.'
