1 TITL Isaac and Ethel Mary (Sproston) Achenbach, family bible
1 ABBR AchenbachIsaacBible
1 AUTH Isaac ACHENBACH
1 NOTE Most information filled in by Ethel M. (Sproston) Achenbach abt. 1955.
2 CONT Some information filled in later.
2 CONT 
2 CONT Pages 25-25
2 CONT 'My life as I remember it.  I was born Ethel Mary Sproston Dec 28, 1898, daughter of George W. and Jennie Collins Sproston.  Lived in Ill. until March 1st, 1904. I moved with my parents to Iowa on a f
2 CONC arm my Dad bought 3 miles S. E. of Sutliff known as the Will Phillips farm. I with my bro. & sisters started to Black Oak Grove school for which I attended until I was 12 yrs old had to quit on accoun
2 CONC t of bad eyes. Had an appendacitis attach when I was 15 yrs but denver mud spread the infection so as I did not have to be operated on. I worked for Grant Hemmingways when I was 15 yrs about 3 weeks b
2 CONC ut as I was never away from home I got homesick & had to go home. In 1915 my Dad sold this farm & we moved about 6 miles S. W. of Anamosa.  Had a nervous breakdown in spring 1916 & was under Dr's car
2 CONC e for sometime. I finally got well enough to work but noise of the little bro. & sisters had to spend most of my time outside so did the garden work for mother. Fell in love with Isaac Achenbach & o
2 CONC n Dec 28, 1916 my 18th Birthday we were married.  The roads were very icy that day. But we hired a neighbor to take us to Marion & my personal record relates the moves we made. I had a stroke in Feb o
2 CONC f 1949 & my health has been rather poorly since. I worked very hard along with my husband all our time on the farm in the fields as well as the garden & house work & raising 6 wonderful children for w
2 CONC hich I am very proud of. I have very few regrets in my life but I know one is that I could of had the money so as I could of kept my children at home longer. I wouldn't of let them work out when the
2 CONC y were so young & my husband & I could of went out together more often instead of working our heads off all the time & staying at home.  I have my grandchildren now to try & make up to them what I cou
2 CONC ldn't to my children. I love every one of them & may God be willing hope to share a good many years with them all. What a wonderful, beautiful world we have so much to be thankful for but so few of u
2 CONC s realize it.  There has been trials & tribulations through my whole life & memories of childhood days that will linger with me all my life.  some are sad & some are good but never to be forgotten
2 CONC . I had such wonder parents & am so proud of them.  Is used to think they were to strict but after I had children of my own, I realized what it was to be a parent. Andrew served 3 yrs 3 mths in servic
2 CONC e in World War 2 & those 3 years put a good many years on me with worry for which know one only a mother can understand.  On June 2nd 1957 I received word that my dear Dad passed away. I lost the dear
2 CONC est most understanding Dad.  May he rest in peace in God's care.  He was 88 yrs old.'
2 CONT 
2 CONT Page 26
2 CONT 'On Nov 25, 1958, my mother's health failed her so much we could not let her live alone anymore  so I volunteered to make a home for her. Her mind is so mixed up. ***GAP***  but am hoping that God wil
2 CONC l give me strength & health so as she will not have to be put in a home. On Sunday P.M. about 6 P.M. Oct 18, 1959, mother had a weak spell & on Tuesday Oct 20, she went into a convulsion about 4 P.M
2 CONC . & never seemed to recover & on Friday evening about 10 P.M. passed away very peacefully. Thank God she did not suffer.  I miss her so very much but she had a full life & loved her family. May God Bl
2 CONC ess & rest her soul. She was 86 yrs old. She was buried in Lisbon Cemetery along side of Daddy. They are both gone but will never be forgotten.'
2 CONT 
2 CONT Page 37
2 CONT 'Issac Achenbach - Attended Union Church in Cedar Bluff until 21 years old. He worked out by the mnth until Dec 28 1916, our Wedding day.
2 CONT He is the father of 7 [written over 6] children. Spent his entire life farming until Oct 8th 1952. he retired from farming due to heart condition & we bought property in C. Bluff. his health is fai
2 CONC r & he keeps busy fishing & working in the gardens & helping mow the lawns & in the winter cracks nuts & keep up his diary each day.  Enjoys visiting with old friends & school mates he used to know du
2 CONC ring his boyhood days.
2 CONT 
2 CONT On Feb 25, 1971 he was taken to Mercy Hospital at Iowa City very ill & was in intensive care until Feb 16 - about 9 P.M. he passed away.' I loved him very dearly & will miss him I know but God knows b
2 CONC est. He gives us life & he also can take it away. May God Bless him he is at rest.  I will join him whenever God calls me.'
